This project is intended to take a dataset of various mushroom attributes to predict whether a mushroom is edible or poisonous.

Link to the UCI data set, Mushroom Binary Classification (Edible: yes/no)

I will perform the following binary classification machine learning models to learn from the data set:

  • Regularized Logistic Regression
    • Lasso
    • Ridge
  • Tree Ensemble
    • Random Forest
    • Gradient Boosted Tree
  • SVM Models
    • Linear Kernel
    • Radial Kernel
  • Artificial Neural Network

Feature Engineering

Imputing Missing Values

There are several features with missing values, the veil-type feature was removed since it was primarily composed of NAs. The remaining features with missing values are as follows,

for (i in 1:dim(mushrooms)[2]) {
  if (any(is.na(mushrooms[i])) == TRUE) {print(colnames(mushrooms[i]))}
}
## [1] "cap.surface"
## [1] "gill.attachment"
## [1] "gill.spacing"
## [1] "stem.root"
## [1] "stem.surface"
## [1] "veil.color"
## [1] "ring.type"
## [1] "spore.print.color"

Given that these are all categorical features and they are considered significant for the information that they provide when it is present, I will need to impute the missing values. I will substitute the missing values for 0. Since R is based on a 1-index, the current factors will not already have a 0 level. Adding a new character value would adjust the feature to a character/mixed type, which will pose significant issues later when trying to encode the categorical data.

I will not divide the data into training/test yet because there is no mathematical imputation with these categorical features that would lead to data leakage.

#replace the missing values
mushrooms$`cap.surface` <- ifelse(is.na(mushrooms$`cap.surface`), 0, mushrooms$`cap.surface`)
mushrooms$`gill.attachment` <- ifelse(is.na(mushrooms$`gill.attachment`), 0, mushrooms$`gill.attachment`)
mushrooms$`gill.spacing` <- ifelse(is.na(mushrooms$`gill.spacing`), 0, mushrooms$`gill.spacing`)
mushrooms$`stem.root` <- ifelse(is.na(mushrooms$`stem.root`), 0, mushrooms$`stem.root`)
mushrooms$`stem.surface` <- ifelse(is.na(mushrooms$`stem.surface`), 0, mushrooms$`stem.surface`)
mushrooms$`veil.color` <- ifelse(is.na(mushrooms$`veil.color`), 0, mushrooms$`veil.color`)
mushrooms$`ring.type` <- ifelse(is.na(mushrooms$`ring.type`), 0, mushrooms$`ring.type`)
mushrooms$`spore.print.color` <- ifelse(is.na(mushrooms$`spore.print.color`), 0, mushrooms$`spore.print.color`)

Now, I can shuffle and divide the data into train, validation, and test sets

library(caret)
set.seed(1)
#shuffle
mushrooms <- mushrooms[sample(nrow(mushrooms), replace = FALSE), ]

Creating a Simple Benchmark

library(ROCR)
bench_table <- table(mush_train$class)
bench_table
## 
##     e     p 
## 15290 19062

The edible class makes up 44.50% of the training data. Therefore, my benchmark will be to predict edible 44.5% of the time.

#specifically takes an integer as input to determine how long the
#returned vector should be
benchmark_predict_fcn = function (x) {
  y = vector(length = x) #vector to store the predictions
   for (i in 1:x) {
      j = (sample(0:1000, size=1))
      if (j < 446) {y[i] = 1} #1 = e (edible)
      else {y[i] = 2} #2 = p (poisonous)
   }
   return (y)
}
#get the predictions
set.seed(1)
benchmark_p <- benchmark_predict_fcn(length(mush_val$class))
benchmark_p <- factor(benchmark_p, levels = c(1,2), labels=c("e", "p"))
table(mush_val$class, benchmark_p)
##    benchmark_p
##        e    p
##   e 1739 2132
##   p 2129 2676

With respect to correctly predicting edible, the metrics of accuracy are as follows:

#Calculate metrics of accuracy
TP = 1739
FP = 2129
FN = 2132
TN = 2676
obs_total <- 1739+2129+2132+2676
bench_specificity = TN / (TN + FP)
bench_precision = TP / (TP + FP)
bench_sensitivity = TP / (TP + FN)
bench_acc <- (1739+2676) / obs_total
f <-(2 * bench_precision* bench_sensitivity) / (bench_precision + bench_sensitivity)
cat("Precision: ", bench_specificity, "\n")
## Precision:  0.5569199
cat("Recall: ", bench_sensitivity, "\n")
## Recall:  0.4492379
cat("F-measure: ", f, "\n")
## F-measure:  0.4494121
#kappa calculations
pred_edible <- (1739+2129) / obs_total
act_edible <- (1739+2132) / obs_total
pred_poison <- (2132+2676) / obs_total
act_poison <- (2129+2676) / obs_total
pr_e <- act_edible * pred_edible + act_poison * pred_poison
bench_kappa <-  (bench_acc - pr_e) / (1 - pr_e)
#construct the ROC curve
bench_pred <- prediction(predictions = as.numeric(benchmark_p), labels = as.numeric(mush_val$class))
bench_perf <- performance(bench_pred, measure = "tpr", x.measure= "fpr")
plot(bench_perf, main = "Benchmark", col = "blue", lwd= 3)
abline(a = 0, b = 1, lwd= 2, lty= 2)

#calculate AUC
bench.perf.auc<-performance(bench_pred, measure = "auc")
bench_auc <- unlist(bench.perf.auc@y.values)

Data Preparation: Scaling & Encoding

SVMs and NNs require numeric data. Therefore it is time to scale and encode the data for use with these models. I will use z-score scaling for the numeric variables.

library(mltools)
library(data.table)

Dummy Encode Categorical Features

I chose to dummy encode the categorical features because one-hot encoding would increase the dimensionality of the data frame, increasing the training time for the more complex machine learning models (such as tree ensembles and SVM).

#copy data over to new dataframe to have an original df and a numeric df
mush_train_num <- mush_train
mush_val_num <- mush_val
mush_test_num <- mush_test
#adjust the true/false features to 0/1 instead of 1/2
#has.ring, and does.bruise.or.bleed
mush_train_num$`has.ring` = ifelse(mush_train_num$`has.ring`=="t", 1, 0)
mush_val_num$`has.ring` = ifelse(mush_val_num$`has.ring`=="t", 1, 0)
mush_test_num$`has.ring` = ifelse(mush_test_num$`has.ring`=="t", 1, 0)
#does.bruise.or.bleed
mush_train_num$`does.bruise.or.bleed` = ifelse(mush_train_num$`does.bruise.or.bleed`=="t", 1, 0)
mush_val_num$`does.bruise.or.bleed` = ifelse(mush_val_num$`does.bruise.or.bleed`=="t", 1, 0)
mush_test_num$`does.bruise.or.bleed` = ifelse(mush_test_num$`does.bruise.or.bleed`=="t", 1, 0)
#convert categorical classes to a number, dummy encode
categorical_cols <- c("cap.shape", "cap.color", "gill.color", "stem.color", "habitat", "season")
mush_train_num[categorical_cols] <- lapply(mush_train_num[categorical_cols], as.numeric)
mush_val_num[categorical_cols] <- lapply(mush_val_num[categorical_cols], as.numeric)
mush_test_num[categorical_cols] <- lapply(mush_test_num[categorical_cols], as.numeric)

Scaling Numeric Features

I will use z-score standardization. The features does.bruise.or.bleed and has.ring will not be scaled, as they are already input on a binary (0/1) scale.

#SCALE NUMERIC VARIABLES
scale_cols = c("cap.diameter", "cap.shape", "cap.surface", "cap.color", "gill.attachment", "gill.spacing", "gill.color", "stem.height", "stem.width", "stem.root", "stem.surface", "stem.color", "veil.color", "ring.type", "spore.print.color", "habitat", "season")

#compute mean and sd of training data
col_means_train <- attr(scale(mush_train_num[,scale_cols]), "scaled:center")
col_stddevs_train <- attr(scale(mush_train_num[,scale_cols]), "scaled:scale")

#scale training data
mush_train_num[scale_cols] = scale(mush_train_num[scale_cols])

#scale validation data based on training data mean and stddev
mush_val_num[scale_cols]<- scale(mush_val_num[scale_cols], center = col_means_train,
                                   scale = col_stddevs_train)
#scale test data based on training data mean and stddev
mush_test_num[scale_cols]<- scale(mush_test_num[scale_cols], center = col_means_train,
                                    scale = col_stddevs_train)

Creating the Neural Network with the best hyperparameters

#create the model
model = keras_model_sequential() %>%
  layer_dense(units = 100,                          #first hidden layer
              activation = 'sigmoid', 
              input_shape = dim(mush_train_num)[2] ) %>%
  layer_dropout(0.7) %>%                            #drop out layer
  layer_dense(units = 100,                          #second hidden layer
              activation = 'sigmoid') %>%
  layer_dropout(0.7) %>%                            #drop out layer
  layer_dense(units = 1,                            #output layer
              activation = 'sigmoid')               #activation must be sigmoid due to binary output
#compile the model
model %>% compile(
  optimizer = optimizer_adam(learning_rate=0.01),
  loss = 'binary_crossentropy',                     #loss must be binary cross entropy due to binary output
  metrics="acc")
#fit the model
set.seed(1)
history <- model %>% fit(as.matrix(mush_train_num),
